   107→// PaintLayer is an old object that handles lots of unrelated operations.
   108→//
   109→// We want it to die at some point and be replaced by more focused objects,
   110→// which would remove (or at least compartmentalize) a lot of complexity.
   111→// See the STATUS OF PAINTLAYER section below.
   112→//
   113→// The class is central to painting and hit-testing. That's because it handles
   114→// a lot of tasks (we included ones done by associated satellite objects for
   115→// historical reasons):
   116→// - Complex painting operations (opacity, clipping, filters, reflections, ...).
   117→// - hardware acceleration (through PaintLayerCompositor).
   118→// - scrolling (through PaintLayerScrollableArea).
   119→// - some performance optimizations.
   120→//
   121→// The compositing code is also based on PaintLayer. The entry to it is the
   122→// PaintLayerCompositor, which fills |composited_layer_mapping| for hardware
   123→// accelerated layers.
   124→//
   125→// TODO(jchaffraix): Expand the documentation about hardware acceleration.
   126→//
   127→//
   128→// ***** SELF-PAINTING LAYER *****
   129→// One important concept about PaintLayer is "self-painting"
   130→// (is_self_painting_layer_).
   131→// PaintLayer started as the implementation of a stacking context. This meant
   132→// that we had to use PaintLayer's painting order (the code is now in
   133→// PaintLayerPainter and PaintLayerStackingNode) instead of the LayoutObject's
   134→// children order. Over the years, as more operations were handled by
   135→// PaintLayer, some LayoutObjects that were not stacking context needed to have
   136→// a PaintLayer for bookkeeping reasons. One such example is the overflow hidden
   137→// case that wanted hardware acceleration and thus had to allocate a PaintLayer
   138→// to get it. However overflow hidden is something LayoutObject can paint
   139→// without a PaintLayer, which includes a lot of painting overhead. Thus the
   140→// self-painting flag was introduced. The flag is a band-aid solution done for
   141→// performance reason only. It just brush over the underlying problem, which is
   142→// that its design doesn't match the system's requirements anymore.
   143→//
   144→// Note that the self-painting flag determines how we paint a LayoutObject:
   145→// - If the flag is true, the LayoutObject is painted through its PaintLayer,
   146→//   which is required to apply complex paint operations. The paint order is
   147→//   handled by PaintLayerPainter::paintChildren, where we look at children
   148→//   PaintLayers.
   149→// - If the flag is false, the LayoutObject is painted like normal children (ie
   150→//   as if it didn't have a PaintLayer). The paint order is handled by
   151→//   BoxFragmentPainter.
   152→// This means that the self-painting flag changes the painting order in a subtle
   153→// way, which can potentially have visible consequences. Those bugs are called
   154→// painting inversion as we invert the order of painting for 2 elements
   155→// (painting one wrongly in front of the other).
   156→// See https://crbug.com/370604 for an example.
   157→//
   158→//
   159→// ***** STATUS OF PAINTLAYER *****
   160→// We would like to remove this class in the future. The reasons for the removal
   161→// are:
   162→// - it has been a dumping ground for features for too long.
   163→// - it is the wrong level of abstraction, bearing no correspondence to any CSS
   164→//   concept.
   165→//
   166→// Its features need to be migrated to helper objects. This was started with the
   167→// introduction of satellite objects: PaintLayer*. Those helper objects then
   168→// need to be moved to the appropriate LayoutObject class, probably to a rare
   169→// data field to avoid growing all the LayoutObjects.
   170→//
   171→// A good example of this is PaintLayerScrollableArea, which can only happen
   172→// be instanciated for LayoutBoxes. With the current design, it's hard to know
   173→// that by reading the code.
